In the token bucket algorithm, the concept of time is typically handled separately from the rate limiter configuration. The token replenish rate determines how many tokens are added to the token bucket per unit time, but it doesn't explicitly define the unit of time itself.

Typically, the time unit is set externally depending on how the rate limiter is being used or where it is being applied. For example, if you want to limit the rate to a certain number of requests per minute, you would set the replenish rate to that desired number and assume that the time unit is minutes.

If you want to adjust the time unit of the rate limiter in your configuration, you can set it explicitly using other mechanisms or calculations. For example, you can calculate the appropriate replenish rate based on units of seconds, minutes, or hours.

